## 13) Forms and Validation
- Use React Hook Form as the standard form library.
- Validate with Zod schemas — one schema file per feature form in `src/features/<feature>/domain/schemas.ts`.
- Keep schemas reusable and importable by both client validation and server actions.
- Show clear field-level errors using `Strings.errors.*` messages.
- Do not embed complex validation logic in JSX markup.

---

## 14) Auth and Role-Based Access
- Firebase Auth (client) is used **only** for the login token exchange (`signInVendorForIdToken` in [`src/lib/auth.ts`](src/lib/auth.ts)).
- **Production session:** httpOnly cookie `__session` via `POST /api/auth/session` — see [`docs/production-security.md`](docs/production-security.md).
- Bootstrap portal session with `GET /api/auth/me` — not `onAuthStateChanged` + direct Firestore.
- Two roles: `admin` and `vendor`. This app is **vendor-only**; admin uses the separate panel.
- **Middleware** ([`src/middleware.ts`](src/middleware.ts)): portal routes require session cookie; auth routes redirect when cookie exists.
- **Guest auth routes** (`/login`, `/register`, `/forgot-password`): `AuthGuestGuard` + middleware. Use **`router.replace`** after login/logout.
- **BFF:** vendor data via [`src/app/api/vendor/*`](src/app/api/vendor/) — never direct Firestore reads from presentation.
- Vendor data isolation: `vendorId` from verified server session only — never from client input.

---

## 15) Error Handling
- Handle errors explicitly at every layer boundary.
- Map infrastructure/Firebase errors to user-friendly messages from `Strings.errors.*`.
- Never expose stack traces, Firebase error codes, or raw exceptions to users.
- Use `error.tsx` at the route level for unrecoverable errors.
- Use error boundaries for isolated section failures.
- Log operational errors server-side, not in user-facing UI.

---

## 16) Server and Client Boundary
- Server Components handle: initial data fetching, auth checks, SEO metadata, static rendering.
- Client Components handle: user interactions, Firebase auth listeners, real-time updates, browser APIs.
- Keep secrets, Firebase service account credentials, and private env vars strictly on the server.
- Never import server-only modules in client components.
- Use `server-only` package for files that must never run in the browser.

---

## 17) Performance
- Minimize unnecessary client-side rendering — default to Server Components.
- Use dynamic imports for heavy client-only modules (rich text editors, image cropper, charts).
- Optimize images with Next.js `<Image>` component — never raw `<img>` for product/vendor images.
- Memoize (`useMemo`, `useCallback`, `memo`) only when profiling shows a real benefit.
- Be intentional about React Query cache TTL and revalidation strategy per feature.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders by keeping props stable and component boundaries clear.

---

## 18) Accessibility
- Semantic HTML first: `<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<header>`.
- All interactive controls have accessible names (`aria-label` when label is not visible).
- Keyboard navigable: all actions reachable via Tab and Enter/Space.
- Status badges and indicators don't rely solely on color — include text label.
- Forms have associated `<label>` elements — not just placeholders.
- Dialogs/modals manage focus correctly (trap on open, restore on close).
- Use `role="status"` or `aria-live` for loading and success feedback.

---

## 19) SEO and Metadata
- Use Next.js `generateMetadata` API for all public-facing pages.
- Vendor portal dashboard pages are auth-protected — no SEO indexing needed.
- Landing page and public vendor storefront pages get full metadata (title, description, og:image).
- Use proper heading hierarchy: one `<h1>` per page, logical `<h2>`/`<h3>` flow.
- Prefer server-rendered content for the landing page.

---

## 20) Navigation and Routing
- Centralize route paths in `src/constants/routes.ts`:
```typescript
export const Routes = {
  home: '/',
  vendor: {
    dashboard: '/vendor/dashboard',
    products: '/vendor/products',
    orders: '/vendor/orders',
    earnings: '/vendor/earnings',
    settings: '/vendor/settings',
  },
  admin: {
    vendors: '/admin/vendors',
    products: '/admin/products',
    orders: '/admin/orders',
  },
  auth: {
    login: '/auth/login',
    register: '/auth/register',
  },
} as const;
```
- Never hardcode URL strings in components — always import from `Routes`.
- Keep navigation patterns consistent; use Next.js `<Link>` for all internal navigation.

---

## 21) Security
- Vendor data isolation enforced in BFF routes + Admin SDK repositories — `vendorId` from verified session cookie, never client input.
- Deploy [`firestore.rules`](firestore.rules) and enable **Firebase App Check** in production (see [`docs/production-security.md`](docs/production-security.md)).
- Sanitize and validate all API input with Zod.
- **Middleware** + **httpOnly session cookie** + **Firebase Admin** `verifySessionCookie` on every `/api/*` route.
- Never expose Firebase Admin credentials, service account keys, or stack traces to clients.
- Production: strip console logs, disable browser source maps, security headers in [`next.config.ts`](next.config.ts).
- Client guards (`PortalSessionContext`, `AuthGuestGuard`) are UX only — authorization lives on the server.

---

## 22) Code Quality
- Keep files and components small enough to stay maintainable.
- Split large modules when complexity grows — no file should do more than one thing.
- Clear naming: files, functions, components, hooks, and variables should be self-documenting.
- Remove dead code, commented-out code, and unused imports.
- Avoid architecture drift — new features follow the same structure as existing ones.

---

## 23) Forbidden Practices
- Business logic embedded in pages or presentational components.
- Firebase imports outside `src/features/<feature>/infrastructure/` or `src/lib/`.
- Raw Firebase Firestore reads in presentation or hooks — use `/api/vendor/*` BFF routes.
- Direct `firebase/firestore` imports outside server infrastructure (`*.admin.repository.ts`, [`src/lib/firebase-admin.ts`](src/lib/firebase-admin.ts)) for vendor data.
- Unnecessary `"use client"` on server-capable components.
- Hardcoded hex values, pixel values, font names, or spacing values in component/module files.
- Hardcoded UI strings as JSX literals, `placeholder`, `aria-label`, or `title` attributes — use `useStrings()` / `getStrings()`.
- Importing `Strings` directly in client components that must respect the active locale — use `useStrings()` instead.
- English-only or Arabic-only partial translations — both `strings.ts` and `locales/ar.ts` must stay aligned via `AppStrings`.
- UI copy in `application/` or `infrastructure/` layers — strings belong in constants + locale files; presentation reads them via hooks.
- Hardcoded URL strings in components — use `Routes.*`.
- Unstyled native `<select>` in portal or feature presentation UI — use `PortalSelect`.
- Raw `<img>` for monochrome SVG UI icons — use `ThemedSvgIcon` with token colors.
- Spinners for page, list, or section content loading — use per-element shimmer skeletons (see §7).
- Single large skeleton blocks representing entire sections — one primitive per visible shape.
- Large monolithic component/page files without decomposition.
- Exposing raw Firebase errors, stack traces, or internal error codes to users.
- Developer-facing or work-in-progress copy in UI (`Strings.*`, toasts, empty states, alerts) — all user-visible text must be production-ready.
- Vendor accessing another vendor's data — isolation is non-negotiable.
- `any` type without strong documented justification.
- Secrets or Firebase Admin credentials in client-accessible code.

